responses.content: Very strong Q2 results. Revenue $7.7B (+32% YoY), exceeded guidance midpoint. Record EPYC and Ryzen sales offset export control headwinds. Free cash flow >$1B.

Revenue $3.2B (+14% YoY). EPYC 5th Gen Turin ramping significantly. Cloud instances grew to nearly 1,200. MI350 series launched with volume production ahead of schedule. MI355 matches/exceeds B200 in critical workloads.
Revenue $3.6B (+69% YoY). Client revenue $2.5B (+67% YoY) led by record desktop sales. Gaming revenue $1.1B (+73% YoY) with semi-custom normalization and new Xbox collaboration.
MI350 ramping H2. MI400 progressing for 2026 (Helios platform). Sovereign AI engagements accelerating (e.g., UMaine). ROCm 7 delivering 3x performance increase.
Department of Commerce reviewing MI308 licenses. Expect to resume shipments if approved. No MI308 revenue included in Q3 guidance.
Revenue $7.7B (+32% YoY). Gross margin 43% (GAAP 40%) due to $800M export control charge. Excluding charge, Non-GAAP GM ~54%. Operating income $897M. EPS $0.48.
Data Center Op Loss $155M due to inventory charge. Client/Gaming Op Income $767M (21% margin). Embedded Op Income $275M (33% margin).
Revenue ~$8.7B (+/- $300M), up ~28% YoY. Driven by MI350 ramp and Data Center double-digit seq growth. Gross Margin ~54%.

questions: Did Q2 include client pull-forward given flat H2 outlook?
Update on China MI308 licenses and supply chain readiness?
answers: Lisa Su: No major pull-forward seen; strong sell-through. Gaining share in premium segments.
Lisa Su: Licenses under review. $800M charge was mostly WIP inventory; will take time to ramp once licensed.
Lisa Su: Additive opportunity. Multi-billion dollar potential (e.g., Saudi Arabia).
Jean Hu: MI margins below corporate average but improving with operational efficiency. Focused on margin dollars.
Lisa Su: Strong ramp Q2 to Q3. MI355 production started in June.
Lisa Su: Developer Cloud revenue not material in H2; strategic for developer access.

questions: MI350 adoption vs expectations 90 days ago?
answers: Lisa Su: Adoption faster/better than expected. Broad interest.
Lisa Su: Client single-digit seq growth Q3. Gaming flat Q3, down strong double-digits Q4 (console seasonality).

questions: How is GM flat sequentially despite GPU ramp (dilutive)?
answers: Lisa Su: Lead times 8-9 months. Strong supply chain.
Jean Hu: Server expansion and Commercial Client mix tailwinds offset gaming/GPU mix headwinds.

questions: Timeline for $10s of billions AI revenue?
Impact of reasoning models on inference complexity?
answers: Lisa Su: Aspiration for future. Requires gigawatt-scale deployments.
Lisa Su: Proliferation of models confirms GPU as compute of choice. Scale-up/out architecture critical.
Jean Hu: Strong double-digit seq growth in Data Center (CPU+GPU). Market share increasing.
Jean Hu: Majority was WIP inventory, not on-shelf finished goods. Takes time to process.

questions: Use of proceeds from ZT manufacturing sale ($3B)?
answers: Lisa Su: Helios on track for significant 2026 contribution.
Jean Hu: Invest in business first, then return cash to shareholders (buybacks).
Jean Hu: Majority driven by MI355 ramp, plus Client/Embedded growth.
Lisa Su: Will take time to ramp; not expecting significant impact in Q3.
